Live Project Activities\nThis document outlines the instructions for the JMeter project activities.\nPrerequisites:\nJMeter\nActivity 1: Recording a Load Test\nInstructions: Try to use only FireFox browser for this activity.\nStart by selecting the Recorder template from the Templates menu:\u000b*\nConfigure the recorder with the following properties and click Create:\nhostToRecord: www.training-support.net\nrecordingOutputFile: recording.xml\nschemeToRecord: https\nOnce the Test Plan is generated, select the HTTP Request Defaults config element and add /selenium to its Path:\u000b*\nSelect the Thread Group and modify it as follows:\nNumber of Threads: 10\nRamp-up Period: 1\nLoop-Count: 10\u000b*\nSelect the HTTP(S) Test Script Recorder controller element and Start the recorder\nWhen the recorder starts, JMeter will generate an authentication certificate for the Recorder Proxy. The certificate is located in JMETER_HOME/bin\u000b*\nAdd the Security Certificate to your Firefox Browser. To add the certificate, please follow the instructions mentioned in the slides.\nTo add the Security Certificate to a Chrome Browser:\nBrowse to the JMETER_HOME/bin, and click on the file ApacheJMeterTemporaryRootCA Security Certificate file, and open it\nClick on the Details tab and check that the certificate details agree with the ones displayed by the JMeter Test Script Recorder.\nIf OK, go back to the General tab, and click on Install Certificate and follow the Wizard prompts.\nOnce the JMeter Proxy is set, navigate through the following pages on the Training Support Selenium site:\nSimple Form\nIFrames\nLogin Form\nTables\nFile Upload\n\u0010\u0012\u001cNote: It is recommended that you open the Training Support Selenium site in a new window without any other tabs open in it. It helps to avoid any other background requests that could be running in the browser window\n\u0011Once you have navigated through all the pages mentioned above, Stop the recorder. Also do not forget to change the Proxy setting in the browser back to what it was set to before.\nThe pages that were visited while the recorder was on will be added as HTTP Requests to the Recording Controller:\u000b*\nWith the HTTP Requests added, you can now run the load test\u000b*\nObserve the results in the View Results Tree listener under the Thread Group:\u000b*\nAdditionally, you may also add a few assertions to the HTTP Requests.\f\nActivity 2: Load Testing an API with Authentication\nInstructions:\nCreate a new Test Plan with a Thread Group with the following:\nNumber of Threads: 5\nRamp-up Period: 1\nLoop Count: 5\nAdd a HTTP Header Manager config element to the Thread Group. Add the following header to it\n\u0010\u0012\u001cAuthorization\n\u001cBearer \u003cAdd GitHub Access Token here\u003e\n\u0011To create a GitHub access token, please refer to the Generating the access token section of this document\n\nNext, add a HTTP Request Default config element with the following defaults:\nProtocol: https\nServer Name: api.github.com\u000b*\nFinally, add a User Defined Variables config element. Add a variable with\nName: sshKey\nValue: \u003cAdd SSH public key here\u003e\nTo get SSH Keys, you can use this website: Generate SSH Keys\n\f\nIn this activity, we will be testing with POST, GET, and DELETE requests.\nAdd a Critical Section Controller element to the Thread Group.\nThe Critical Section Controller ensures that its children elements (samplers/controllers, etc.) will be executed by only one thread. You can read more about it here: JMeter docs\nAll the HTTP requests that we will be testing will be added under this Critical Section Controller.\nAdd a HTTP Request sampler element with the method set to POST and the Path set to /user/keys. \nUnder the Body Data tab, enter the JSON request body as shown:\u000b*\nHere, ${sshKey} is a variable that we set in the User Defined Variables Config element. To use the variable value, the syntax is ${variableName}.\nUnder the POST Request, add a JSON Extractor post process element. This will be used to get the id of the SSH Key that we just added.\nConfigure the JSON Extractor with the following parameters:\nName of the created variables: browser for this activity.\nStart by selecting the Recorder template from the Templates menu:\u000b*\nConfigure the recorder with the following properties and click Create:\nhostToRecord: www.training-support.net\nrecordingOutputFile: recording.xml\nschemeToRecord: https\nOnce the Test Plan is generated, select the HTTP Request Defaults config element and add /selenium to its Path:\u000b*\nSelect the Thread Group and modify it as follows:\nNumber of Threads: 10\nRamp-up Period: 1\nLoop-Count: 10\u000b*\nSelect the HTTP(S) Test Script Recorder controller element and Start the recorder\nWhen the recorder starts, JMeter will generate an authentication certificate for the Recorder Proxy. The certificate is located in JMETER_HOME/bin\u000b*\nAdd the Security Certificate to your Firefox Browser. To add the certificate, please follow the instructions mentioned in the slides.\nTo add the Security Certificate to a Chrome Browser:\nBrowse to the JMETER_HOME/bin, and click on the file ApacheJMeterTemporaryRootCA Security Certificate file, and open it\nClick on the Details tab and check that the certificate details agree with the ones displayed by the JMeter Test Script Recorder.\nIf OK, go back to the General tab, and click on Install Certificate and follow the Wizard prompts.\nOnce the JMeter Proxy is set, navigate through the following pages on the Training Support Selenium site:\nSimple Form\nIFrames\nLogin Form\nTables\nFile Upload\n\u0010\u0012\u001cNote: It is recommended that you open the Training Support Selenium site in a new window without any other tabs open in it. It helps to avoid any other background requests that could be running in the browser window\n\u0011Once you have navigated through all the pages mentioned above, Stop the recorder. Also do not forget to change the Proxy setting in the browser back to what it was set to before.\nThe pages that were visited while the recorder was on will be added as HTTP Requests to the Recording Controller:\u000b*\nWith the HTTP Requests added, you can now run the load test\u000b*\nObserve the results in the View Results Tree listener under the Thread Group:\u000b*\nAdditionally, you may also add a few assertions to the HTTP Requests.\f\nActivity 2: Load Testing an API with Authentication\nInstructions:\nCreate a new Test Plan with a Thread Group with the following:\nNumber of Threads: 5\nRamp-up Period: 1\nLoop Count: 5\nAdd a HTTP Header Manager config element to the Thread Group. Add the following header to it\n\u0010\u0012\u001cAuthorization\n\u001cBearer \u003cAdd GitHub Access Token here\u003e\n\u0011To create a GitHub access token, please refer to the Generating the access token section of this document\n\nNext, add a HTTP Request Default config element with the following defaults:\nProtocol: https\nServer Name: api.github.com\u000b*\nFinally, add a User Defined Variables config element. Add a variable with\nName: sshKey\nValue: \u003cAdd SSH public key here\u003e\nTo get SSH Keys, you can use this website: Generate SSH Keys\n\f\nIn this activity, we will be testing with POST, GET, and DELETE requests.\nAdd a Critical Section Controller element to the Thread Group.\nThe Critical Section Controller ensures that its children elements (samplers/controllers, etc.) will be executed by only one thread. You can read more about it here: JMeter docs\nAll the HTTP requests that we will be testing will be added under this Critical Section Controller.\nAdd a HTTP Request sampler element with the method set to POST and the Path set to /user/keys. \nUnder the Body Data tab, enter the JSON request body as shown:\u000b*\nHere, ${sshKey} is a variable that we set in the User Defined Variables Config element. To use the variable value, the syntax is ${variableName}.\nUnder the POST Request, add a JSON Extractor post process element. This will be used to get the id of the SSH Key that we just added.\nConfigure the JSON Extractor with the following parameters:\nName of the created variables:
